Connect1-Stigma: 1. Logistic regression

Logistic regression with backwards elimination

Method

The participants in this analysis were n=753 who have a four-frequency PTA of > 25 dB HL in their better ear and no missing data in 28 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable. These 753 cases were randomly split into 7 similarly-sized folds, each containing a similar rate of hearing aid purchase (about 19.8%). To get an idea of how much the model performance varied across different subsets of data, the same logistic regression analysis was conducted 7 times, each time dropping out one fold of data (about 15% of cases).

Each logistic regression model had 28 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable (purchase = ‘Yes’; 1, or ‘No’; 0). After the initial regression with 28 predictors, a backwards elimination procedure based on AIC was conducted to exclude any predictors that led to worse performance by the model. To evaluate the accuracy, sensitivity and specificity of each model, predicted outcomes were considered to be ‘Yes’ cases if the predicted probability was equal to or greater than the rate of purchase in that particular fold of data (e.g., if a case has an outcome probability of 0.2567 as predicted by the model, and the rate of purchase in that subset of data is 0.1987, then that case was considered to be a ‘Yes’ case).

A final logistic regression model was then performed with the entire set of 753 cases.

Results

Using logistic regression to predict hearing aid purchase from 28 demographic, health, and social variables, model accuracy ranged from 64% to 67% across different subsets of data, model sensitivity ranged from 57% to 66%, and model specificity ranged from 64% to 67%. Predictors that appeared in at least 6 of 7 subsets of data were: Age and HHIE (strong), Health, HA Stigma, and “know someone with suspected HL” (weak).

The final model constructed with all data had an overall accuracy of 66% for predicting hearing aid purchase, with 61% sensitivity and 67% specificity. Predictors in the final model were: Age and HHIE (strong), Health, HA Stigma, “know someone with suspected HL”, and “discussed HL with someone” (weak).

Conclusion

According to a logistic regression analysis, age and HHIE helped predict hearing aid purchase in this sample, but the model prediction performance was quite poor.
